Looking at the target sorry, I need to prove that there exists a functor that doesn't preserve non-isomorphisms. In other words, I need to find a functor that maps a non-isomorphism to an isomorphism.

A classic example is the functor from a discrete category with two objects to the terminal category (with one object). Any morphism in the codomain is an isomorphism (the identity), but in a discrete category, the only morphisms are identities, so we need a different approach.

Better example: Consider a functor from a category with two distinct objects and only identity morphisms to a category with one object. But we need a non-identity morphism that becomes an isomorphism.

Actually, the simplest example is: Take a monoid viewed as a category (one object) where we have a non-invertible element, and map it to a trivial monoid where everything is invertible.

Even simpler: Take the category with two objects and three morphisms (two identities and one non-iso from one object to another), and map both objects to the same object in the codomain.

